The system (25)–(27) is a model for describing the time evolution of an epidemic in terms of the statistical distribution of social contacts, without taking into account any external intervention. However, protection measures such as lockdown strategies inevitably cause reduction in the average number of social contacts of the population which can be taken explicitly into account in our model. In the epidemiological literature, a natural way to introduce this mechanism, which dates from the work of Capasso and Serio (Capasso and Serio 1978), consists in considering a non linear incidence rate whose main feature is to be bounded with respect to the number of infected. Interestingly, on this subject, we aim to highlight that a similar behavior of the incidence rate can be directly derived starting from our social-SIR model (25)–(27). The additional hypothesis that is sufficient to introduce is that the average number \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
